---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<BaseLayout title="Prayer Corner Guide" description="How to set up a prayer corner at home — the 'beautiful corner' that anchors your daily life in the presence of God.">

  <section class="article-hero">
    <div class="hero-content">
      <div class="section-label" style="margin-bottom:16px;">Practical Guide</div>
      <h1 class="hero-title" style="font-size:34px;">Setting Up a Prayer Corner</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">
        The "beautiful corner" — a sacred space in your own home.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="article-surface">
    <div class="container--narrow">
      <nav class="breadcrumbs">
        <a href={`${base}/`}>Home</a>
        <span class="sep">›</span>
        <a href={`${base}/tools/`}>Tools</a>
        <span class="sep">›</span>
        <span style="color: var(--beeswax);">Prayer Corner</span>
      </nav>

      <article class="article-body">

        <p class="drop-cap">In Ukrainian: <em>sviatyi kut</em>, the "holy corner." In Greek: <em>ikonostási</em>. In Russian: <em>krasny ugol</em>. The name changes with the language. The idea does not. A dedicated space in the home, set apart for prayer, where a person stands before God each day.</p>

        <p>Not a shrine. Not a mini-church. Something more practical: a place. Prayer needs a place. Not because God lives in one corner and is absent from another, but because human beings are creatures of space and habit. A specific corner where prayer happens trains the body to expect prayer the way a desk trains the body to expect work.</p>

        <figure class="article-image">
          <img src="/byzantine-doors/images/iconostasis.jpg" alt="An iconostasis with icons arranged in traditional order" />
          <figcaption>A church iconostasis — the prayer corner at home follows the same principle on a smaller scale: icons arranged deliberately, creating a window into the sacred.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>What You Need</h2>

        <p>Keep it simple. No major investment. No renovation. The minimum:</p>

        <div class="checklist">
          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-icon">☦</span>
            <div>
              <strong>An icon of Christ.</strong> Non-negotiable. Start here. A paper print works fine. The most traditional choice is Christ Pantocrator ("Ruler of All"), but any canonical icon of Christ will do.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-icon">☦</span>
            <div>
              <strong>An icon of the Theotokos.</strong> The Mother of God, placed to the left of Christ (from your perspective). The Vladimir icon is one of the most beloved: tender, intimate, her cheek pressed against the Child's.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-icon">☦</span>
            <div>
              <strong>A candle or oil lamp.</strong> Light it when prayer begins. Extinguish when prayer ends. This act, striking the match, watching the flame, becomes a signal to body and soul: it is time.
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="checklist-item">
            <span class="checklist-icon">☦</span>
            <div>
              <strong>A prayer book.</strong> Any Eastern Christian prayer book with morning and evening prayers. Memorization comes slowly. It is not expected.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>Four things. A cross, a patron saint icon, holy water, blessed palms can be added over time. But these four are enough to begin.</p>

        <figure class="article-image">
          <img src="/byzantine-doors/images/theotokos-vladimir.jpg" alt="The Vladimir Icon of the Theotokos" />
          <figcaption>The Vladimir Icon of the Theotokos — one of the most copied and beloved icons in Eastern Christianity. Her tenderness is theology: God became small enough to be held.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h2>Where to Place It</h2>

        <p>The traditional instruction: face <strong>east</strong>. Not superstition. Symbolism. Christ is called the "Sun of Righteousness" and the "Dayspring from on high." Early Christians prayed toward the rising sun, expecting Christ's return from the east.</p>

        <p>If east is not practical (bathroom wall, parking lot view), choose the next best option:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>A quiet corner of a bedroom or living room</li>
          <li>Away from television and screens</li>
          <li>Visible enough to pass daily (a prayer corner hidden in a closet will be forgotten)</li>
          <li>Not in a high-traffic hallway</li>
          <li>If children are present, make it accessible to them. Let them see prayer. Let them light the candle.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>A small shelf, a table, the top of a bookcase, a wall-mounted bracket. The corner does not need to be large. Some of the most powerful prayer corners are barely two feet wide.</p>

        <h2>Which Icons to Start With</h2>

        <p>Beyond Christ and the Theotokos:</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Patron saint</strong> — the saint whose name was received at baptism or chrismation</li>
          <li><strong>Feast icon of the current season</strong> — swap throughout the year (Nativity at Christmas, Resurrection at Pascha)</li>
          <li><strong>Family patron saints</strong> — spouse's and children's saints</li>
          <li><strong>A saint you feel drawn to</strong> — particular devotion to specific saints is normal and encouraged</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Arrangement: Christ on the right (as you face the corner), Theotokos on the left. Others to the sides or below. A cross at top center if desired. No rigid formula, but a clear hierarchy. Christ always holds the place of honor.</p>

        <h2>How to Pray There</h2>

        <p>Stand. Light the candle. Make the sign of the cross. Begin.</p>

        <p>The Byzantine tradition offers structured morning and evening prayers: psalms, troparia, the Creed, prayers of repentance, prayers for the living and the dead. Found in any Orthodox prayer book. Designed to be read aloud, slowly.</p>

        <p>A beginner's rule might include:</p>

        <ol>
          <li>The Trisagion prayers (a short opening sequence used before almost all Eastern prayers)</li>
          <li>The Lord's Prayer</li>
          <li>A psalm (Psalm 50/51 is the classic prayer of repentance)</li>
          <li>A few minutes of the Jesus Prayer</li>
          <li>Personal prayers, in your own words</li>
          <li>Closing prayers and the sign of the cross</li>
        </ol>

        <p>Ten minutes. That is enough. Consistency forms more deeply than duration. Ten minutes every morning in front of the icons will do more than an hour-long spiritual binge once a month.</p>

        <div class="pastoral-note">
          <p><strong>Ask your priest</strong> for a prayer rule. In the Byzantine tradition, the specific prayers and their length are worked out with a spiritual father. He will give something suited to the circumstances. What matters is having <em>a</em> rule and keeping it, not having the longest one.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Living With It</h2>

        <p>Over time, the prayer corner becomes more than furniture. It becomes the spiritual center of the home: the place for mornings and evenings, anxieties and gratitude, boredom and grief.</p>

        <p>The icons will watch. That sounds strange until you have lived with icons for a while. They do not judge. They do not demand. They look. Steadily, quietly, from a place beyond time. Their looking is a reminder: always seen, always known, always loved.</p>

        <p>A shelf. Two icons. A candle. Light it tomorrow morning. Stand there. Breathe. Say the words.</p>

        <p>That is enough.</p>

      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article-hero {
    padding: 80px 40px 32px;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .article-body {
    padding-bottom: 80px;
  }
  .article-body p,
  .article-body li {
    font-size: 17px;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    margin-bottom: 20px;
  }
  .article-body h2 {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 26px;
    font-weight: 400;
    color: var(--beeswax);
    margin: 48px 0 16px;
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
  }
  .article-body .drop-cap::first-letter {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: 56px;
    float: left;
    color: var(--halo-gold);
    opacity: 0.7;
    line-height: 0.8;
    margin: 8px 14px 0 0;
    font-weight: 400;
  }
  .article-body ul, .article-body ol {
    padding-left: 24px;
    margin-bottom: 24px;
  }
  .article-body li {
    margin-bottom: 10px;
  }
  .article-body em {
    color: var(--censer-smoke);
  }

  .article-image {
    margin: 36px 0;
    text-align: center;
  }
  .article-image img {
    max-width: 100%;
    max-height: 500px;
    border: 0.5px solid var(--gold-10);
    border-radius: 8px;
    box-shadow: 0 4px 24px rgba(0,0,0,0.3);
  }
  .article-image figcaption {
    font-family: var(--font-ui);
    font-size: 12px;
    color: var(--deep-muted);
    margin-top: 10px;
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .checklist { margin: 24px 0 32px; }
  .checklist-item {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px;
    padding: 16px 0;
    border-bottom: 0.5px solid var(--gold-06);
    align-items: flex-start;
  }
  .checklist-icon {
    font-size: 20px;
    color: var(--halo-gold);
    opacity: 0.6;
    flex-shrink: 0;
    margin-top: 2px;
  }
  .checklist-item div {
    font-size: 15px;
    color: var(--aged-vellum);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }
  .checklist-item strong {
    color: var(--beeswax);
  }

  .pastoral-note {
    border-left: 2px solid var(--halo-gold);
    background: var(--gold-04);
    border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0;
    padding: 20px 24px;
    margin: 32px 0;
  }
  .pastoral-note p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  @media print {
    body { background: white; color: black; }
    .article-body p, .article-body li { color: #333; }
    .article-body h2 { color: #111; }
    .checklist-item div { color: #333; }
    .checklist-item strong { color: #111; }
    .pastoral-note { border-left: 2px solid #666; background: #f5f5f5; }
    .breadcrumbs, nav { display: none; }
    .article-image img { box-shadow: none; border: 1px solid #ccc; }
  }
</style>
